<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" ?>

<chapter xml:id="ch17-data-mining" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Hi Ho, Hi Ho &#x2014; Data Mining We Go</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Data mining is an area of research and practice that is focused on discovering novel
      patterns in data. As usual, R has lots of possibilities for data mining. In this
      chapter we will begin experimentation with essential data mining techniques by trying
      out one of the easiest methods to understand: association rules mining. More beer and
      diapers please!
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-datamining-overview">
    <title>What Is Data Mining?</title>

    <p>
      Data mining is a term that refers to the use of algorithms and computers to discover
      novel and interesting patterns within data. One famous example is the supermarket
      that analyzed patterns of purchasing behavior and found that diapers and beer were
      often purchased together. The supermarket manager decided to put a beer display close
      to the diaper aisle and supposedly sold more of both products as a result.
    </p>

    <p>
      Some people refer to this area of research as <term>machine learning</term>. Machine
      learning focuses on creating computer algorithms that can use pre-existing inputs to
      refine and improve their own capabilities for dealing with future inputs. Data mining
      typically consists of four processes:
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li><p><em>Data preparation</em>&#x2014;making sure that the data are organized in
        the right way, filling in missing data fields, locating and repairing inaccurate
        data, and recoding data as necessary.</p></li>
      <li><p><em>Exploratory data analysis</em>&#x2014;getting to know the data using
        histograms and other visualization tools, and looking for preliminary hints that
        will guide model choice.</p></li>
      <li><p><em>Model development</em>&#x2014;the most complex and interesting activity:
        testing out a selection of the most appropriate data mining techniques.</p></li>
      <li><p><em>Interpretation of results</em>&#x2014;the most important step from the
        perspective of the data user, where an actionable conclusion is formed.</p></li>
    </ol>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-association-rules">
    <title>Association Rules Mining</title>

    <p>
      The technique we will use in this chapter is called <term>association rules
      mining</term> (also sometimes called affinity analysis). It is the strategy that was
      used to find the diapers and beer association described earlier.
    </p>

    <p>
      The association rules algorithm tries out many different propositions, such as <q>if
      diapers are purchased, then beer is also purchased.</q> The algorithm uses a dataset
      of transactions (individual shopping carts) to evaluate a long list of these rules
      for two quantities:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><term>Support</term>: The proportion of times that a particular pairing
        occurs across all transactions.</p></li>
      <li><p><term>Confidence</term>: How frequently a particular pair occurs among all
        the times when the first item is present.</p></li>
      <li><p><term>Lift</term>: A measure of interestingness, calculated as the ratio of
        the rule's confidence to the baseline probability of the consequent item appearing
        in any transaction.</p></li>
    </ul>

    <figure xml:id="fig-ch17-association-rules-diagram">
      <caption>A conceptual diagram of association rules mining: each customer has a
      cart of items from the store inventory, and the algorithm finds associations
      between items across all transactions.</caption>
      <image source="ch17-association-rules-diagram.png" width="80%">
        <description>A diagram with three columns: Customers (Customer 1, Customer 2,
        Customer 3), Carts (boxes listing items each customer has selected), and Store
        Inventory (a list of products such as Baby Wipes, Beer, Bread, Cheddar, Chips,
        Corn Flakes, Diapers, Lettuce, Mayonnaise, Milk, Peanut Butter, Salami, Shampoo,
        Sponges, Tomatoes, and Toothpaste). Lines connect items in each cart to the
        corresponding products in the store inventory, illustrating the transaction data
        used in association rules mining.</description>
      </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
      We can get started with association rules mining very easily using the R package
      known as <c>arules</c>:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch17-arules">
      <code>
install.packages("arules")
library(arules)
data(Groceries)
summary(Groceries)
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      The <c>Groceries</c> dataset built into the <c>arules</c> package contains 9,835
      transactions with 169 items. The most frequent items include whole milk, other
      vegetables, rolls/buns, and soda.
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch17-itemfreq">
      <code>
itemFrequencyPlot(Groceries, topN=8)
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      This command produces the following plot:
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-ch17-itemfreq-plot">
      <caption>A bar chart showing the relative item frequency for the eight most common
      items in the Groceries dataset.</caption>
      <image source="ch17-itemfreq-plot.png" width="70%">
        <description>A bar chart with the y-axis labeled "item frequency (relative)"
        ranging from 0.00 to 0.25, and eight items on the x-axis: tropical fruit, root
        vegetables, other vegetables, whole milk, yogurt, rolls/buns, bottled water, and
        soda. Whole milk has the tallest bar at around 0.25, followed by other vegetables
        at about 0.19.</description>
      </image>
    </figure>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-apriori">
    <title>Running the Apriori Algorithm</title>

    <p>
      The main function in the <c>arules</c> package is <c>apriori()</c>. We can pass it
      the grocery transaction data and specify minimum support and confidence thresholds:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch17-apriori">
      <code>
ruleset &lt;- apriori(Groceries,
  parameter=list(support=0.01, confidence=0.5))
inspect(ruleset)
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      To explore a broader set of rules, we can be more lenient in our minimum support
      and confidence parameters, and then use the <c>arulesViz</c> package to visualize
      the results:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch17-viz">
      <code>
install.packages("arulesViz")
library(arulesViz)
ruleset &lt;- apriori(Groceries,
  parameter=list(support=0.005, confidence=0.35))
plot(ruleset)
goodrules &lt;- ruleset[quality(ruleset)$lift > 3.5]
inspect(goodrules)
      </code>
    </program>

    <figure xml:id="fig-ch17-rules-scatter-plot">
      <caption>The output of <c>plot(ruleset)</c>: a scatter plot of 357 association
      rules with support on the x-axis, confidence on the y-axis, and lift shown by
      the shade of each point.</caption>
      <image source="ch17-rules-scatter-plot.png" width="70%">
        <description>A scatter plot titled "Scatter plot for 357 rules". The x-axis
        shows support values from 0.01 to 0.07, and the y-axis shows confidence values
        from 0.35 to 0.70. Each rule is represented by a small square whose shade
        indicates lift, with a legend on the right side ranging from 1.5 (light) to 4
        (dark). Most rules are clustered at low support values near 0.01, with confidence
        spread across the full range.</description>
      </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The visualization plot shows support on the X-axis, confidence on the Y-axis, and
      lift indicated by the darkness of each dot. Focusing on rules with high lift reveals
      combinations that may correspond to recipes: herbs with root vegetables, or tropical
      fruit with curd and yogurt.
    </p>

  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch17">
    <title>Chapter Challenge</title>
    <exercise xml:id="ex-ch17-challenge">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <c>arules</c> package contains other data sets, such as the <c>Epub</c>
          dataset with 3975 transactions from the electronic publication platform of the
          Vienna University of Economics. Load up that data set, generate some rules,
          visualize the rules, and choose some interesting ones for further discussion.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </exercises>

